label.value: increased protein level during mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to vacuole, with protein mislocalized to cytosol

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein localization to the vacuole does not occur, and the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization via NVT pathway

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the vacuole lumen via the NVT pathway is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal macroautophagy during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which macroautophagy is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. Macroautophagy is the major pathway by which cells digest parts of their own cytoplasm.

label.value: abolished macroautophagy during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which macroautophagy does not occur when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

label.value: increased negative regulation of transcription by glucose

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which negative regulation of transcription by glucose (glucose repression) occurs to a greater extent than normal. Specific genes that are normally not transcribed in the presence of glucose are not derepressed in the mutant under conditions that derepress transcription in wild type cells.

label.value: increased 5.8S rRNA length

value.value: A phenotype in which the processed 5.8S ribosomal RNA is longer than normal.

label.value: abnormal 5.8S rRNA 3'-end processing

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mature 3' end of the 5.8S ribosomal RNA molecule is abnormal.

label.value: increased chromatin silencing at centromere outer repeat

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing at centromere outer repeat regions is increased.

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin. See the GO cellular component term 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792), and the biological process term 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828).

label.value: increased protein localization to chromatin at centromere inner repeat

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at centromere inner repeat regions is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished ribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which a ribonuclease activity is absent.

label.value: abolished intra-arm chromosome contact change during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which changes in contacts within a chromosome arm that normally take place during mitosis do not occur.

label.value: decreased protein localization to actomyosin contractile ring, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the actomyosin contractile ring is decreased, and some of the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: medial F-actin spot present

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which F-actin forms a large spot in the medial region of the cell, instead of assembling into a contractile ring.

label.value: normal actin monomer binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of a protein to one or more actin monomers is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant actin-binding protein may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with actin filaments that is assayed in a mutant, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal actin filament-based process

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which an actin filament-based process, i.e. any process that depends upon or alters the actin cytoskeleton, is abnormal.

label.value: decreased actin filament severing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin filament severing is decreased. Actin filament severing is the process in which an actin filament is broken down into smaller filaments.

label.value: thick actin cables in medial region

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells form actin cables that are thicker than normal in the medial region of the cell.

definition.value: Cells with this phenotype usually have thick actin cables instead of a well-formed contractile ring near the midpoint of the cell, when the ring would normally form and contract during cytokinesis.

label.value: increased nucleosome occupancy at FLEX element

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleosome occupancy is greater than normal at promoters containing FLEX elements. Nucleosome occupancy measures the tendency for DNA in a given region to be packaged into nucleosomes.

label.value: abnormal DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity is abnormal.

label.value: abolished DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity is absent.

label.value: decreased DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of DNA-3'-diphospho-5'-guanosine diphosphatase activity is decreased.

label.value: abolished meiotic G2/MI transition

value.value: A cell phenotype in which progression from meiotic G2 phase to M phase of meiosis I does not occur.

label.value: abolished ascus formation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which formation of the ascus, the sac-like structure that encloses spores, does not occur.

label.value: abolished homologous chromosome segregation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome segregation does not occur. Homologous chromosome segregation is the process in which replicated homologous chromosomes are organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two sets during the first division of the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: spindle pole bodies present in increased numbers during meiosis II

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which cells contain more spindle pole bodies (SPBs) than normal during the second meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: decreased protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body during meiosis II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle pole body is decreased during the second meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term. Use this term for cells in which in which the re-accumulation of some spindle pole body components does not occur at the onset of meiosis I.

label.value: decreased DNA resection during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the extent of DNA resection upstream of a stalled replication fork is lower than normal. DNA resection is the 5'-to-3' degradation of one strand of DNA, leaving a stretch of single-stranded DNA.

label.value: normal extent of DNA resection during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the extent of DNA resection upstream of a stalled replication fork is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). DNA resection is the 5'-to-3' degradation of one strand of DNA, leaving a stretch of single-stranded DNA.

label.value: normal replication slippage during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the increase in small deletions or duplications ("replication slippage") that normally results from processing arrested replication forks is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at stalled replication fork

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at stalled replication forks is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to chromatin at stalled replication fork

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at stalled replication forks is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: loss of viability following replication fork stalling

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after stalled replication forks accumulate.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under conditions that cause replication fork stalling, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth (without fork stalling) is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: normal septin ring morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, and structure of the septin ring is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: elongated multinucleate vegetative cell with multinucleate compartment

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is elongated, may contain a septum, and contains multiple nuclei (usually four or more) per compartment.

label.value: decreased protein localization to medial cortical node

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical nodes is decreased in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal rate of protein exchange in medial cortical node

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of protein exchange in the medial cortical nodes is abnormal. Normally, myosin and other node proteins are turned over between the nodes and elsewhere at rates consistent for each protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein level in spliceosomal complex

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of a protein measured in any spliceosomal complex is lower than normal.

definition.value: Use this term for cases where the relative abundance of one or more specific proteins in the proteasome is decreased, altering the proteasome stoichiometry. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal organelle localization

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which organelle localization, i.e. any process in which an organelle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location, is abnormal.

label.value: decreased endoplasmic reticulum-plasma membrane tethering

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the attachment of an endoplasmic reticulum membrane to the plasma membrane via molecular tethers occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased mating efficiency during stationary phase

value.value: A biological process phenotype in which the observed mating efficiency, as determined by counting zygotes, asci, and sometimes spores, is lower than normal when the population in which the mating cells are found is in stationary phase.

definition.value: Note that mating efficiency is often measured by counting zygotes plus asci, sometimes also including spores, so a change in measured mating efficiency may reflect a change in conjugation frequency (see FYPO:0000031 and its descendants), a change in sporulation (see FYPO:0000121 and its descendants), or both. For this reason, this term is not a child of 'mating phenotype' (FYPO:0000031).

label.value: normal mating efficiency during stationary phase

value.value: A biological process phenotype in which the observed mating efficiency, as determined by counting zygotes, asci, and sometimes spores, is normal (i.e. the same as in wild-type cells) when the population in which the mating cells are found is in stationary phase.

definition.value: Note that mating efficiency is often measured by counting zygotes plus asci, sometimes also including spores, so a change in measured mating efficiency may reflect a change in conjugation frequency (see FYPO:0000031 and its descendants), a change in sporulation (see FYPO:0000121 and its descendants), or both. For this reason, this term is not a child of 'mating phenotype' (FYPO:0000031).

label.value: decreased zinc ion binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of zinc ion binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds zinc less than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene decreases zinc binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: decreased RNA level during cellular response to zinc ion starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during a cellular response to zinc ion starvation is lower than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased microtubule nucleation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleation of microtubules from one or more microtubule organizing centers (MTOCs) occurs to a lesser extent than normal.

label.value: decreased mitotic microtubule nucleation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleation of microtubules from one or more microtubule organizing centers (MTOCs) occurs to a lesser extent than normal during mitosis.

label.value: decreased interphase microtubule nucleation from spindle pole body

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nucleation of cytoplasmic microtubules from the spindle pole body (SPB) occurs to a lesser extent than normal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle. Normally, microtubules are nucleated from interphase microtubule organizing centers (iMTOCs) and from the cytoplasmic face of the SPB.

label.value: nucleus mislocalized towards cell tip during mitotic telophase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the divided nuclei are located near the cell tips (instead of at the midpoint of the long axis of each daughter cell) during telophase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: mononucleate vegetative cell with mislocalized nucleus

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell has one nucleus that is not in the normal location.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: endocytosis restricted to old cell end

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which endocytosis occurs only at the old end of the cell during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle. Normally, endocytosis takes place at the old cell end throughout interphase, and also at the new end after NETO.
